How to finance green transformation.
New York – This week, world leaders gathered in New York at the United Nations to assess the global war on climate change and submit new carbon-emission pledges.
Climate crisis is a matter of great urgency, but our pace of action is far from sufficient.
We are slow to shift into high gear.
Accelerating the pace of change requires concerted efforts from all sectors, public and private alike.
Fortunately, thanks to the work of the Climate Finance Leadership Initiative (CFLI), private sector collaboration on mitigating climate change is growing increasingly prevalent.
Under the leadership of UN Climate Ambassador Michael Bloomberg, CFLI was established, with the goal of mobilizing global private capital to address this critical issue.
This month, CFLI has released a new report, Financing the Low Carbon Future, which outlines how to expand green finance to support an orderly low-carbon economic transition and presents opportunities for public-private collaboration to achieve the 2015 Paris Agreement goals.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) is the world's largest multilateral investor in climate-related projects.
But in response to the call by the heads of state of the European countries and the newly elected President of the European Commission, Ursula von der Leyen, we are now preparing to mobilize even greater ambition, to strengthen the role of EIB as the EU's dedicated climate bank.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) will mainstream climate considerations, target low-carbon investments, and will commit at least €1 trillion over the next decade to low-carbon projects.
To achieve this goal, at least 50% of EIB financing will be used for climate action and environmental sustainability by 2025.
By the end of 2020, we will align all our financing activities with the goals of the Paris Agreement.
As a crucial first step, we will exclude energy projects that rely on fossil fuels.
In addition, we will position EIB as a green finance incubator, committed to mobilizing additional resources to help economies transition to a low-carbon future.
As a bank of the EU, our mission is to invest in Europe's future, and the most pressing issue among them is climate change.
The climate crisis is as urgent as our resolve.
Just this summer, Europe faced record-high temperatures and crop failures, caused by last year's drought.
Many developing countries have had similar experiences.
Flooding and other climate-related phenomena annually exact tens of billions of dollars from major cities, posing an even greater threat to human life.
But the climate crisis is also an opportunity, as financing for new green infrastructure can create jobs, stimulate economic growth, and reduce air pollution that plagues major cities worldwide.
Changing our investment approach will accelerate the transition away from fossil fuels. This transition is already underway.
Market forces increasingly favor clean energy and a transition away from fossil fuels.
In 2011, nearly half of the US coal-fired power plants had retired, while the clean energy sector created over 3.3 million jobs, compared to less than 100,000 in the coal industry.
In addition, an increasing number of cities and states in the US have committed to achieving net-zero emissions by 2050.
They will receive support from Beyond Carbon, a plan launched by the Bloomberg Philanthropies last year to support the complete decarbonization of the US economy.
As the international community, we not only have to invest in clean energy but also reduce investment in dirty energy.
Currently, from the perspective of fossil fuel subsidies, we are essentially still investing in promoting climate change and air pollution.
These public funds should be used to guide investment towards electric vehicles and other transformative technologies that can drive a green transition.
These investments will yield substantial returns, including significant cost savings from the massive health burden imposed by air pollution on public health.
In addition to redirecting public funds, we can also take numerous steps to channel necessary financing.
First, we must enhance data and disclosure standards.
For decades, businesses and investors have been oblivious to climate-related risks, unaware of the rationale for reducing carbon emissions or shielding their assets from extreme weather impacts.
This momentum is starting to shift.
The Task Force on Climate-related Financial Disclosures' recommendations are guiding companies to allocate capital in a more sustainable manner, and enabling investors to reward companies that take climate change seriously.
Secondly, we must clarify investment risks related to green finance.
Most cities contribute 70% or more of global CO2 emissions, but only a small number of cities in developing countries have access to credit ratings.
As a result, total investments in clean buses, energy-efficient buildings, and other emission-reducing projects have been impacted.
The government and listed banks must step up their efforts to help cities attract capital for these projects, including through initiatives like the Global Covenant of Mayors for Climate & Energy, which is supported by the EIB and co-led by Bloomberg Philanthropies.
Thirdly, we need to modernize the grid.
Subsidies and tax incentives have promoted the expansion of wind and solar power, reducing costs for businesses and consumers.
Now, we should introduce similar initiatives to accelerate the deployment of battery storage and other emerging technologies, to speed up overcoming intermittency issues.
Better grid connectivity can allow surplus regions with wind and solar power to supply power to regions in demand.
The government can play a leading role in both areas, encouraging more private investment to flow into clean power.
Finally, we must continue to expand the green investment market.
In 2007, the EIB issued the world's first green bond on the Luxembourg Stock Exchange, since then, the green bond market has grown to €136 billion.
Compared to the global bond market of $100 trillion, it's just a drop in the ocean.
Therefore, the EIB is helping the EU develop sustainable finance standards classification, so that investors can compare like-for-like projects, just as with standard bonds.
Better and more information about carbon footprints can enable investors to make informed decisions, thereby driving more private investment into low-carbon projects.
This is the method we use to finance green transition.
